its from their education. Their divergent educational outcomes, she contends, stemmed from Chicago officials’ decision to deal with rising African American migration by segregating schools and denying black students equal resources. And it deepened, she shows, because of techniques for managing academic failure that only reinforced inequality. Ultimately, these tactics eroded the legitimacy of the schools in Chicago’s black community, leaving educators unable to help their most disadvantaged students. Schools Betrayed will be required reading for anyone who cares about urban education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, inner city, poverty, community, neighborhood, urban, student success, test scores, preparation, learning outcomes, academic achievements, nonfiction, curriculum, sociology, politics, race, chicago, public school, immigrants, class, status, segregation, great migration, resources, management, failure, legitimacy, trust, disadvantaged, racism, labor, classroom, vocational, remedial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022656960440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226569628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226569628/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles